prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
Custom mosaic: The entire Snake nebula can be covered by a custom mosaic of 145 Nyquist sampled pointings at the observing frequencies. We have used the JCMT 850 micron image ([ref 22], resolution 14.5 arcsec) as a guide for dense gas to make the mosaic. To recover the multi-scale structures (Fig. 2) we request a combined 12m+ACA+TP mosaic.
Correlator setup: The correlator setup is optimized to simultaneously observe 3mm continuum as well as N2H+(1-0) and HNC(1-0) lines. We use baseband-1 to receive N2H+(1-0) at 0.1 km/s spectral resolution, baseband-2 to receive HNC (1-0) and CH3CN (5-4) at 0.2 km/s resolution, and the other two 1.875 GHz wide basebands are used for continuum and H2CS (new thermometer) and SO2 (outflow tracer) at 3 km/s resolution. The requested spectral resolutions ensure fine kinematics to be resolved by N2H+. HNC is less bright as N2H+ (peak flux half of N2H+) in the Mopra data [ref 30], so we request a wider spectral resolution. The K ladder of CH3CN is used to measure the warm gas temperature in active star forming clumps.
We invest a small amount of data rate to receive low resolution H2CS to explore for the first time its potential as a thermometer, similar to H2CO. The multiple H2CS transitions covered in baseband-3,4 have upper-state energy levels of 9, 22, and 63 K, and therefore trace cold and warm gas in the cloud. Should the extra data rate is too expensive, we agree to change basebands 3 and 4 to continuum mode; this way the total data rate is within 12MB/s and will not affect our main science goals.
Sensitivity: We request 2 arcsec (0.03 pc) angular resolution to resolve the ~0.1 pc cores, and a continuum sensitivity of 0.2 mJy/beam to sample the dense core population for fragmentation analysis and mass function study. The continuum sensitivity corresponds to 2 Msun (assuming 15 K temperature and the same dust emissivity law as our SMA study [ref 18]), similar to our SMA sensitivity at the finest resolution (Fig. 2, right panels). The mass sensitivity and spatial resolution are better than the Jeans mass and length of the clumps, sufficient to study fragmentation.
According to the OT and the ALMA sensitivity calculator, the corresponding line sensitivity is about 1.7, 0.1, and 0.03 K per 0.2 km/s in the 12m array (resolution 2 arcsec), ACA (resolution 22 arcsec), and TP (resolution 66 arcsec), respectively. The Mopra data has a resolution (38 arcsec) between the ACA and TP, and measures a peak N2H+ brightness of 2 K (~1K for HNC) after correction for main beam efficiency [ref 30]. This results a peak S/N of about 20. We do not have sufficient information to estimate the brightness seen by the 12m array. However, towards smaller scales the N2H+ and HNC are expected to centrally peak around dense cores, so the brightness will be significantly higher. Should the N2H+ and HNC emission have the same spatial distribution as dust emission, we estimate S/N~8 for the 12m array. If the sensitivity turns out to be insufficient, we will smooth the spectral lines (up to 0.4 km/s, FWHM linewidth ~1.7 km/s from Mopra data) and/or smooth the angular resolution (up to 3 arcsec), without substantial negative impact on our science goals.
Telescope time: Under the default weather condition recommended by OT (PWV=5.186mm), the requested sensitivity can be achieved in 2.26 hr in 12m array and a factor of 4 in the ACA+TP.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract:
Recent Herschel images have shown increasing evidence that star forming dense cores are preferentially located along dense ridges (or filaments) in molecular clouds, but little is known how these cores are formed in the context of filamentary structures, especially in the high-mass case.
We propose to obtain high fidelity mosaic images in 3mm dust continuum and N2H+/HNC (1-0) lines of the filamentary IRDC G11.11-0.12, a high-mass analogue to the well-studied low-mass star forming filament Taurus L1495/B213. This IRDC represents a quasi-sinusoidal shaped filament containing hierarchical structures at multiple scales from ~1 pc down to ~0.01 pc. The proposed observations will enable us to study the detailed kinematics associated with the hierarchical structures, and to investigate how dense cores form and evolve physically and chemically within filaments.
The proposed study will (1) provide a full picture of the structures, kinematics, dense core formation and evolution, of a giant molecular cloud that has a simple filamentary morphology, (2) have a distinguishing power to leading high-mass star formation scenarios, and (3) set a model for other filamentary complexes.
